The Ouadi Fractal-Entropy Framework: A Unified Theory of Autonomous Industrial Ecosystems

Author: Ouadi Maakoul
Date: March 2026

Abstract

This dissertation presents the Ouadi Fractal‑Entropy Framework (OFEF) , a purely theoretical synthesis of fractal geometry, information theory, and graph‑based dynamics for modeling autonomous industrial ecosystems. The framework introduces a three‑layer fractal hierarchy (component, system, ecosystem) that captures the recursive, self‑similar structure of technology systems. Each technological node is associated with a probability distribution over Technology Readiness Levels (TRLs), grounding Shannon entropy as a measure of technological uncertainty. Mutual information quantifies pairwise dependencies, and transfer entropy captures directional causal influence. The central contribution is the operationalisation of Partial Information Decomposition (PID) within a fractal technology network, showing that systemic resilience depends on distinguishing redundancy (positive higher‑order interactions) from synergy (negative higher‑order interactions). The Ouadi Graph Neural Network (OGNN) is a dynamic message‑passing framework that simulates entropy propagation and identifies keystone nodes; its stability and convergence are proved under explicit conditions. All results are derived mathematically, with rigorous proofs and algorithmic specifications. No empirical experiments are conducted; the work establishes a theoretical foundation for future empirical and applied research. The dissertation concludes with operational strategic foresight principles derived from the framework and a robustness analysis for approximate self‑similarity.

