Chapter 2: Literature Review

2.1 Technology Roadmapping and Readiness Levels

Technology roadmaps (Phaal et al., 2004) provide linear maturity projections. Technology Readiness Levels (TRLs) from NASA are the de facto standard for measuring maturity. Extensions like System Readiness Levels (Sauser et al., 2008) integrate integration dependencies but remain deterministic.

2.2 Network Models of Innovation

Innovation ecosystems are often modeled as networks where nodes are technologies, firms, or institutions, and edges represent citations, collaborations, or dependencies (Schilling & Phelps, 2007). Metrics such as centrality and clustering coefficient reveal structural features, but uncertainty and causality are rarely incorporated.

2.3 Information Theory in Complex Systems

Shannon entropy (Shannon, 1948) measures uncertainty. Mutual information (Cover & Thomas, 2006) quantifies statistical dependence. Transfer entropy (Schreiber, 2000) extends to directional causality. Applications include measuring knowledge flows (Leydesdorff, 2003), supply chain resilience (Garvey et al., 2015), and industrial alarm causation (Röth et al., 2019).

2.4 Fractal Geometry and Self‑Similar Networks

Fractals (Mandelbrot, 1982) exhibit self‑similarity across scales. Network fractals (Song et al., 2005) display power‑law degree distributions and scale‑invariant clustering. Fractal properties have been observed in manufacturing networks (Yu et al., 2020) and supply chains.

2.5 Graph Neural Networks

GNNs (Kipf & Welling, 2017) process graph‑structured data. They have been applied to dynamic systems (Battaglia et al., 2018). Fractal‑inspired GNN variants have been proposed to mitigate over‑squashing, but none combine a provable multi‑layer fractal hierarchy with entropy propagation.

2.6 Partial Information Decomposition (PID)

Partial Information Decomposition (Williams & Beer, 2010) formalises the decomposition of multivariate mutual information into unique, redundant, and synergistic components. For three variables, the mutual information $I(X;Y,Z)$ can be written as $I_{\text{unique}}(X;Y) + I_{\text{unique}}(X;Z) + I_{\text{red}}(X;Y,Z) + I_{\text{syn}}(X;Y,Z)$. Redundant information is shared among multiple sources; synergistic information is only accessible when sources are considered together. This directly underpins the OFEF’s interpretation of higher‑order interactions in technology resilience.

2.7 Digital Twins for Industrial Ecosystems

Digital twins (Grieves, 2014; Tao et al., 2019) are virtual representations that enable simulation and optimisation. The OGNN, as a dynamic graph‑based simulation of entropy propagation, functions as a digital twin of the technology ecosystem. Unlike conventional digital twins that focus on real‑time monitoring and physics‑based models, the OGNN is an information‑theoretic abstraction designed specifically for resilience and foresight.

2.8 Complexity Economics and Technology Evolution

Complexity economics (Arthur, 1999; Farmer et al., 2022) emphasises non‑linear dynamics, path dependence, and emergent phenomena. The OFEF’s strategic foresight claims align with the view that technologies co‑evolve in networks of influence; the framework offers a formal information‑theoretic grounding.

2.9 Research Gap

No existing work integrates a self‑similar fractal hierarchy, PID‑informed information metrics, a dynamic GNN with stability guarantees, and a purely theoretical validation into a unified framework for technology ecosystems. This dissertation fills that gap.

