A.3 Decomposition of Total Correlation and PID

We provide a formal derivation of the inclusion–exclusion expansion for total correlation and its connection to Partial Information Decomposition (PID).

For n random variables X_1,\dots,X_n, the total correlation is

C(X_1,\dots,X_n) = \sum_{i=1}^n H(X_i) - H(X_1,\dots,X_n).

Using the chain rule for entropy,

H(X_1,\dots,X_n) = \sum_{i=1}^n H(X_i \mid X_1,\dots,X_{i-1}).

Thus

C = \sum_{i=1}^n \bigl( H(X_i) - H(X_i \mid X_1,\dots,X_{i-1}) \bigr) = \sum_{i=1}^n I(X_i; X_1,\dots,X_{i-1}),

where I(X_i; X_1,\dots,X_{i-1}) is the mutual information between X_i and the set of previous variables. Expanding this mutual information using the chain rule for mutual information gives

I(X_i; X_1,\dots,X_{i-1}) = \sum_{j=1}^{i-1} I(X_i; X_j \mid X_1,\dots,X_{j-1}).

Hence

C = \sum_{i=1}^n \sum_{j=1}^{i-1} I(X_i; X_j \mid X_1,\dots,X_{j-1}).

The inclusion–exclusion expansion in terms of unconditional mutual informations and higher‑order terms is more involved. A standard combinatorial identity (Cover & Thomas, 2006, Problem 2.29) states that for any set of variables,

H(X_1,\dots,X_n) = \sum_{i=1}^n H(X_i) - \sum_{i<j} I(X_i;X_j) + \sum_{i<j<k} I(X_i;X_j;X_k) - \cdots + (-1)^{n-1} I(X_1;\dots;X_n),

where the higher‑order mutual informations are defined recursively: I(X_1;X_2;X_3) = I(X_1;X_2) - I(X_1;X_2 \mid X_3), and so on. This yields directly

C = \sum_{i<j} I(X_i;X_j) - \sum_{i<j<k} I(X_i;X_j;X_k) + \cdots + (-1)^n I(X_1;\dots;X_n).

Now PID (Williams & Beer, 2010) decomposes the mutual information between a set of source variables and a target variable into unique, redundant, and synergistic components. For the special case where the target is one variable and the sources are the remaining n-1 variables, the PID gives a finer decomposition of the terms in the expansion. In particular, the higher‑order mutual information I(X_1;\dots;X_n) can be expressed as a combination of redundant and synergistic components. In the context of technology resilience:

· Positive higher‑order mutual information (e.g., I(X_i;X_j;X_k) > 0) indicates redundancy: the information that is common to all three variables.
· Negative higher‑order mutual information indicates synergy: the information that only becomes available when the variables are considered together, and is not present in any subset.

Therefore, to assess resilience, one should not only look at total correlation C but also at the sign pattern of higher‑order interactions. The OFEF operationalises this by advising that in critical systems, positive higher‑order interactions should be promoted to ensure graceful degradation, whereas negative higher‑order interactions (synergy) should be minimised because they create hidden single points of failure.

