Appendix C: Mathematical Background

C.1 Review of Shannon Entropy, Mutual Information, Transfer Entropy

Shannon Entropy: For a discrete random variable X with probability mass function p(x), the entropy H(X) = -\sum_x p(x) \log_2 p(x) (bits). It measures the average uncertainty about X.

Joint Entropy: H(X,Y) = -\sum_{x,y} p(x,y) \log_2 p(x,y).

Conditional Entropy: H(X|Y) = H(X,Y) - H(Y) = -\sum_{x,y} p(x,y) \log_2 p(x|y).

Mutual Information: I(X;Y) = H(X) + H(Y) - H(X,Y) = \sum_{x,y} p(x,y) \log_2 \frac{p(x,y)}{p(x)p(y)}. It is symmetric and non‑negative, zero iff X and Y are independent.

Transfer Entropy: For two discrete‑time stochastic processes X_t, Y_t, the transfer entropy from Y to X is

TE_{Y\to X} = \sum p(x_{t+1}, x_t, y_t) \log_2 \frac{p(x_{t+1} | x_t, y_t)}{p(x_{t+1} | x_t)}.

It measures the reduction in uncertainty about the next state of X due to knowledge of the past of Y, beyond the past of X itself. It is non‑negative and zero iff Y does not Granger‑cause X.

C.2 Review of Partial Information Decomposition (PID)

Given a target variable T and source variables S_1,\dots,S_m, the PID (Williams & Beer, 2010) decomposes the mutual information I(T; S_1,\dots,S_m) into non‑negative contributions:

· Unique information U(T;S_i): information that only source S_i provides.
· Redundant information R(T; \{S_i\}_{i\in A}): information that is common to all sources in a set A.
· Synergistic information S(T; \{S_i\}): information that is only available when all sources are considered together.

The decomposition satisfies:

I(T; S_1,\dots,S_m) = \sum_i U(T;S_i) + \sum_{|A|\ge 2} R(T;A) + S(T; \{S_i\}).

The higher‑order mutual information terms in the inclusion–exclusion expansion can be expressed as combinations of these PID components. In the context of the OFEF, we use this framework to interpret the sign of higher‑order mutual informations: positive values indicate redundancy; negative values indicate synergy.

C.3 Review of Fractal Dimension and Box‑Counting

The box‑counting dimension of a set (or a graph) is defined as

D = \lim_{\epsilon \to 0} \frac{\log N(\epsilon)}{\log(1/\epsilon)},

where N(\epsilon) is the minimum number of boxes of side length \epsilon needed to cover the set. For a graph, we place a grid over the nodes in an embedding (e.g., using a metric derived from the adjacency) and count how many boxes contain at least one node. In self‑similar networks, the number of nodes scales as N \sim \epsilon^{-D}, and the same exponent appears at different scales. The fractal dimension invariance theorem in the main text states that if the three layers are self‑similar with the same power‑law exponent, then their box‑counting dimensions are equal.

